"{\n  \"text\": \"I've heard concerns in the past about using RO water filter, and that is too thin a water. It becomes hungry. It wants to leach out minerals from other things to balance itself because you've taken too much of it out. I don't know exactly if this is true or not. I've just heard that concern. Personally, I think most Americans have a problem with too much salt, and a little bit of dilution of that salt might be a good thing. Of course, if it's leaching out important minerals that we don't have enough of, then that's a bad thing. But one of the things that you can do with that is you can mix a little bit of salt in, not enough to make it salty, but just enough to kind of balance it. A naturally found sea salt or Himalayan salt works great for this. And if that's a concern of yours, I would certainly recommend doing that. For me personally, I've been drinking RO water for ages. I've never experienced any of these effects. And when I ferment with it, I'm mixing salt with it already. So uh that's the issue as far as I see it. I'm not a scientist, don't know for sure if that's the case, but that's my thinking on it. Thanks, y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" I've heard concerns in the past about using RO water filter, and that is too thin a water.\",\n      \"start\": 0.8,\n      \"end\": 6.24,\n      \"duration\": 5.44,\n      \"confidence\": 0.986,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" I\",\n          \"start\": 0.8,\n          \"end\": 1.04,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 0.997\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"'\",\n          \"start\": 1.04,\n          \"end\": 1.2,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.998\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ve\",\n          \"start\": 1.2,\n          \"end\": 1.28,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" he\",\n          \"start\": 1.28,